412→                           The values of $f(k)$ are known as Schur numbers. The best-known bounds for large $k$ are\[(380)^{k/5}-O(1)\leq f(k) \leq \lfloor(e-\tfrac{1}{24}) k!\rfloor-1.\]The lower bound is due to Ageron, Casteras, Pellerin, Portella, Rimmel, and Tomasik <a href="#cite-ACPPRT21-483" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ACPPRT21','483'); return false;">[ACPPRT21]</a> (improving previous bounds of Exoo <a href="#cite-Ex94-483" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Ex94','483'); return false;">[Ex94]</a> and Fredricksen and Sweet <a href="#cite-FrSw00-483" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('FrSw00','483'); return false;">[FrSw00]</a>) and the upper bound is due to Whitehead <a href="#cite-Wh73-483" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Wh73','483'); return false;">[Wh73]</a>. Note that $380^{1/5}\approx 3.2806$.<br><br>The known values of $f$ are $f(1)=2$, $f(2)=5$, $f(3)=14$, $f(4)=45$, and $f(5)=161$ (see <a href="https://oeis.org/A030126" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">A030126</a>). (The equality $f(5)=161$ was established by Heule <a href="#cite-He17-483" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('He17','483'); return false;">[He17]</a>).<br><br>See also <a href="/183" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[183]</a> (in particular a folklore observation gives $f(k)\leq R(3;k)-1$).
